<HEADLINE>
<P>
NBA ROUNDUP; JORDANAIRES WILL PLAY ON AS A SINGLES ACT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 There were no celebrations in Chicago. No hooting. No hollering. 
</P>
<P>
 Been there. Done that. 
</P>
<P>
 The Bulls clinched a return trip to the playoffs and a chance to defend their 
NBA championship a third time Tuesday night with a 106-103 victory over the 
Philadelphia 76ers. 
</P>
<P>
 So what? They knew they would be back, whether Michael Jordan plays the 
outfield or not. 
</P>
<P>
 "We proved a lot of people wrong. We're third in the East. We planned on being 
very competitive. We took a lot of pride," Scottie Pippen said after his 27 
points led the Bulls. 
</P>
<P>
 "There's nobody pouring champagne. We expected to make the playoffs. It was a 
forgone conclusion," said Steve Kerr, who made two free throws with 5.6 seconds 
to play. 
</P>
<P>
 The future is less bright for Philadelphia. The 76ers lost their eighth in a 
row and 23rd in 24 games, though they made the Bulls, who led by 10 points 
after three quarters, earn the victory. 
</P>
<P>
 But close doesn't count. "It's not a moral victory," guard Dana Barros said. 
"We aren't going to remember if we played well or not. It's a loss." 
</P>
<P>
 Atlanta 101, New Jersey 98 -- Kevin Willis and Duane Ferrell scored six points 
apiece in the final 4:08 as the Hawks rallied to win in Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
 It was their sixth victory in seven games and gave the Hawks the league's best 
home record, 31-5. The Nets' three-game winning streak ended. 
</P>
<P>
 Ferrell sank two free throws to give Atlanta a 91-90 lead it held for good. 
</P>
<P>
 Willis had 24 points and 16 rebounds for Atlanta. Johnny Newman and Kenny 
Anderson led New Jersey with 17 points apiece. 
</P>
<P>
 New York 106, Charlotte 95 -- Charles Oakley, a doubtful starter because of a 
knee sprain, had 22 points and 17 rebounds at New York as the Knicks won their 
14th in a row. 
</P>
<P>
 The streak is their longest since a team-record 18 in a row in 1969-70. 
</P>
<P>
 The victory was a product of the New York reserves, who, led by Anthony 
Mason's 17 points, outscored the Hornets' backups, 45-17. 
</P>
<P>
 San Antonio 117, Dallas 92 -- David Robinson dominated inside with 37 points, 
22 in the first half, as the Spurs won at Dallas and handed the Mavericks their 
15th consecutive defeat. 
</P>
<P>
 Robinson, who also had seven rebounds, six assists and five blocks, moved past 
Orlando's Shaquille O'Neal into the NBA scoring lead with a 29.2 average as the 
Spurs won their 50th game of the season. 
</P>
<P>
 The Mavericks completed their first winless calendar month in club history, 
finishing March with a 0-13 record. 
</P>
<P>
 Detroit 123, Miami 115 -- Sean Elliott scored eight of his 16 points in the 
final 3:06 as the Pistons won at Miami. 
</P>
<P>
 Joe Dumars paced Detroit with 30 points, all but five in the first and third 
quarters. Terry Mills added 20 for the Pistons, who shot 58%. 
</P>
<P>
 Matt Geiger scored 23 points for Miami, which lost its fifth consecutive game. 
</P>
<P>
 Orlando 120, Washington 101 -- Shaquille O'Neal had 25 points and 10 rebounds 
at Orlando where the Magic tied a club record with its 41st victory. 
</P>
<P>
 Don MacLean had 23 points and Rex Chapman 16 for Washington, which has lost 
nine in a row and 25 of 28. 
</P>
<P>
 Boston 119, Milwaukee 107 -- Rick Fox had a career-high 33 points and sank six 
free throws in overtime in Milwaukee to lead the Celtics to their third victory 
in a row. 
</P>
<P>
 The Bucks have lost five consecutive games. 
</P>
<P>
 Golden State 116, Utah 113 -- Latrell Sprewell scored 35 points, six in the 
final minute, as the Warriors withstood a fourth-quarter comeback to defeat the 
Jazz at Salt Lake City. 
</P>
<P>
 Seattle 114, Portland 100 -- Shawn Kemp scored 28 points, 16 in the third 
quarter, and the SuperSonics pulled away in the fourth at Portland in winning 
for the sixth time in a row. 
</P>
<P>
 The Trail Blazers have lost two consecutive games at home after winning 11 in 
a row. 
</P>
<P>
 Houston 122, Sacramento 101 -- Otis Thorpe scored 21 points and grabbed 18 
rebounds, and seven Rockets scored in double figures in winning at Sacramento. 
</P>
<P>
 Houston played without center Hakeem Olajuwon because of a one-game suspension 
and also without guard Vernon Maxwell and forward Carl Herrera for much of the 
game because of ejections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
