<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY NEWSWATCH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Ann Conwa; Zan Dubin, PPMAN, ; Lee Romney 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 COUNTERPOINT: Friends of Hillary Rodham Clinton are fighting back against her 
critics over Whitewater. Nearly 100 of them took out a full-page ad in the New 
York Times this week to show their support. Among them: Laguna Beach's Janice 
Johnson, whose husband, Roger, is General Services Administration director. . . 
. Johnson, who donated $1,000 for the ad, says: "I think it's great. I'm proud 
to support it. It puts in better words than I can how I feel about Hillary at 
this point. I thought I'd better put my money where my mouth is." 
</P>
<P>
 CARING NEIGHBORS: Diana Colosio, wife of slain Mexican presidential candidate 
Luis Donaldo Colosio, will soon receive condolences postmarked Orange County. 
Los Amigos of Orange County, led by Latino community leaders, will send a 
letter after its weekly meeting in Anaheim today. . . . Says Los Amigos 
Chairman Amin David: "Not only do we express our sorrow for her and her kids' 
tremendous loss, but also for the loss to Mexico." 
</P>
<P>
 BEYOND GAMES: Willie Herron of Laguna Hills is one of five artists 
commissioned to paint murals across Los Angeles for the World Cup soccer 
tournament beginning in June. Eight games will be played in Los Angeles, and 
murals will be painted along freeways and at LAX. . . . Herron's mural, "Solo 
Unido, Un Mundo Vencera," will express the meaning of its title, which conveys, 
Herron says, "the hope that one day we can be a victorious world if all the 
races unite." 
</P>
<P>
 WINDOW DRESSING? There's interest in Cypress in enforcing an old city 
ordinance that prohibits businesses from blocking more than 10% of their 
windows with ads. It's to help police protect against burglary. Problem is, 
merchants love to advertise and tend to ignore the law. . . . City Atty. John 
E. Cavanaugh got a laugh this week when he told the City Council: "We're not 
required by law to enforce our own ordinances." . . . The merchants can rest 
awhile -- the Cypress council hasn't decided what to do. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA033094-0087 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 027486 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
March 30, 1994, Wednesday, Valley Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Part A; Page 1; Column 1 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
312 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
VALLEY NEWSWATCH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Michael Arkush 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 SHAKEDOWN: The streets are quickly mending, and so are our spirits. Life after 
the quake does, indeed, go on in the Valley. But so do the aftershocks -- more 
than 6,000, in fact, since Jan. 17 (B5). The frequency, according to Caltech, 
dropped dramatically after the first day, but we are far from quaked out. . . . 
Seismologists say there's a greater than 1-in-3 chance of another magnitude 5 
in the next year. 
</P>
<P>
 GETTING HELP: In the meantime, people affected by the quake are still seeking 
help from the government. Starting today, a new Earthquake Service Center will 
open in Sherman Oaks, absorbing services that had been provided at two disaster 
application centers that closed Tuesday. . . . Officials were serving about 150 
people a day at each of the two centers (B1). 
</P>
<P>
 CHINA CARD: One of the big issues facing President Clinton is whether to 
revoke China's most-favored-nation trade status because of its poor record on 
human rights. Well, one Valley scholar thinks that Clinton should keep the 
status quo. . . . "When people gain economic independence," said Shao-Ju Lee, 
director of the China Institute at Cal State Northridge, "they look for 
political freedom." 
</P>
<P>
 OVERTIME: The Japanese work ethic is legendary these days and, apparently, it 
extends to the baseball diamond as well. Shizuoka Commercial High, which 
recently visited the Valley, routinely holds six-hour practices, and its 
pitchers throw 200 pitches a day (C6). . . . But you can bet that this is one 
area where America won't try to copy Japan. "Your arm can only take so many 
throws," El Camino Real High pitcher Randy Wolf said. 
</P>
<P>
 TICKETS GALORE: Apparently Santa Clarita is no place to double-park. Since the 
city began processing parking violations in October, the number of tickets 
issued by sheriff's deputies has increased nearly 60%. And no one seems to know 
why (B6). Michael Arkush 
</P>
</TEXT>
